  "prompt": "How does modern Greek language differ from ancient Greek?",
  "response": "Modern Greek (Demotic Greek or Dimotiki) differs from Ancient Greek (Katharevousa) in several key aspects:\n\n1. Pronunciation\n- Ancient Greek had a complex pitch accent system\n- Modern Greek uses stress accents\n- Pronunciation has significantly changed\n\n2. Grammar\n- Ancient Greek had more complex grammatical cases (nominative, genitive, etc.)\n- Modern Greek has simplified case system\n- Verb conjugations are less complicated\n- Word order is more flexible in modern Greek\n\n3. Vocabulary\n- Many Ancient Greek words are no longer used\n- Modern Greek has borrowed words from Turkish, Italian, and other languages\n- Some Ancient Greek words remain but with different meanings\n\n4. Alphabet\n- Basic alphabet remains similar\n- Some letter sounds have changed\n- Orthography has been simplified\n\n5. Syntax\n- Ancient Greek had more complex sentence structures\n- Modern Greek syntax is more straightforward\n- Less reliance on participles and infinitives\n\n6. Verb System\n- Ancient Greek had more verb forms and tenses\n- Modern Greek verb system is more streamlined\n- Fewer irregular verbs\n\n7. Linguistic Evolution\n- Modern Greek developed through Koine Greek, Byzantine Greek, and other transitional phases\n- Influenced by historical and cultural developments\n\nThese differences make Ancient and Modern Greek somewhat mutually unintelligible.",
